article.description: Sheri Sam scored 24 points and fueled a late surge as the Miami Sol ended the New York Liberty's four-game winning streak with a 54-46 victory.
article.headline: Sol's 24 helps Sol cling to final playoff spot
article.linkText: Sam scores 24, helps Sol cool off Liberty
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Sheri Sam scored 24 points, grabbed six rebounds and had three steals as the Miami Sol snapped the New York Liberty's four-game winning streak with a 54-46 victory Tuesday night. Sam, the only Miami player in double figures, scored over 20 points for the fourth time this year. Her 3-point shot with 2:02 remaining pushed Miami's lead to 49-42, and the Liberty never challenged. "Let's face it, she carried us offensively,'' Miami coach Ron Rothstein said. "We got her some good looks and she made some big shots. She also put the ball on the floor and took it to the basket ... She's our All-Star player and we need her.'' The Sol had lost two of three games, while New York entered having won six of seven. Miami (11-12) made only 20 of 58 shots from the field (34.5 percent), while New York (14-10) converted just 16 of 50 shots (32 percent). Sol point guard Debbie Black scored only two points on free throws, going 0-for-7 from the field, but she had eight rebounds, four assists and four steals. She fed Sam in perfect position for her late 3-pointer. "I'm just thinking score, trying to be aggressive and make something happen,'' Sam said. "Debbie did a good job of finding me off the screen. When you get open for a shot like that, you've got to knock it down. That was huge.'' Kristen Rasmussen scored nine points and pulled down eight rebounds for Miami, which remained a half game ahead of Orlando for the final playoff berth in the Eastern Conference. "Right now this is our playoffs,'' Sam said. "I don't want our season to end ... how we play these next 10 games is going to decide if we have a second season.'' Crystal Robinson led the Liberty with 12 points, and Vickie Johnson scored 10. Becky Hammon scored nine in a reserve role. Down by one at halftime, Miami took the lead for good with 3:35 remaining on an 8-foot jumper by Sam. Miami led by five points with 9:49 left before New York went on a 7-2 run. "Down the stretch we just didn't have it,'' New York's Teresa Weatherspoon said. New York committed 17 turnovers that led to 16 Miami points. "Everyone comes to compete. Everyone expects to win,'' Hammon said. "By no means did we take this game lightly. A big part of the story was turnovers.'' Both the Sol and Liberty missed 11 of their first 15 shots and 15 of their first 20. Betty Lennox missed all six of her first-half attempts for Miami. Tari Phillips missed five in a row for the Liberty. Phillips, who leads New York with a 14.3 scoring average, finished with six points. "It was a hard-fought battle, obviously,'' New York coach Richie Adubato said. "Two teams that played as hard as they could play. The difference was Sheri Sam.''

Game notes
Weatherspoon played in her 178th consecutive game, tops in the WNBA. ... Miami has gone 9-3 since putting Vanessa Nygaard at forward and moving Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough to center in place of Ruth Riley. ... The game featured the two youngest players in the league in New York's 19-year-old Bernadette Ngoyisa and Miami's Iziane Castro Marques who is 20. ... Miami's Debbie Black (four) and Betty Lennox (three) had season highs in steals.
